 of natural resources and environmental control was not created until  and there was no authority to regulate solid waste until   from  to  dpl sluiced ash from the coal burners onto the eastern  of burton island berms were built from ash and dredge spoils excess water ran into indian river or island creek this resulted in the elevation of the ground surface by about ± feet over roughly  acres of the island and the wholesale conversion of tidal marshes and flats to upland “fly ash was used to construct a perimeter berm system berms were constructed at a height of approximately  feet consisting of approximately a  foot base of soil  feet of fly ash and a  foot cap of bottom ash by the mid ’s the system of berms and access roadways was completed on the eastern end of the island” on july th  dnrec secretary john hughes issued an order approving the “final plan of remedial action for burton island ash disposal area operable units  and  the landfill consists of  operable units an operable unit is a term used to describe a number of separate activities undertaken as part of a superfund site cleanup ous as follows ou shoreline intertidal zone and vicinity within the footprint of the portion of the erosion control project surrounding the landfill ou the landfillland areas landward inside of the footprint of the erosion control project ou the subtidal sediments and the waters seaward outside of the footprint of the erosion control project the order approves the following actions be taken ou nrg and indian river power llc irpllc intend to install erosion controlbank stabilization measures along ou the erosion control measures consist of installation of armor stone and large concrete blocks underlain by geotextile synthetic fabric along the shorelines of burton island enhancement or creation of tidal marsh along shoreline areas where wave energies are sufficiently low to permit its survival ou nrg and irpllc intend to take no further action with respect to ou the plan does not address operable unit  “ou” which is the area where dpl disposed of the coal ash ou was not considered in the plan because this area is still the subject of an ongoing department environmental remediation investigation including all storm water and groundwater issues the july   order no a at page  states the investigation would be completed in  ou because of its size and heterogeneity will need to be investigated in greater detail before a feasibility study can be conducted and a remedy selected in april  planning for the ou ri is reported in progress and field work was expected to start later in   a plan of remediation was proposed for ou in january  and was adopted october   httpwwwdnrecdelawaregovinfodocumentssecretarysordernowhpdf final plan of remedial action for burton island ash disposal area operable units  and  august   httpwwwdnrecstatedeusdnrecdivisionsawmsirbfinalplansgmdpdf proposed plan of remedial action for burton island ash disposal area operable units  and  april  httpwwwdnrecstatedeusdnrecdivisionsawmsirbproposedplansproposedplanburtonislandpdf burton island ash disposal area presentation httpwwwawmdelawaregovsirbdocumentsburtonioverviewforpublicpdf phase i landfill  the acre phase i coal ash landfill permit no sw issued january   is located approximately onehalf mile southwest of the power station construction of phase i was initiated in  and coal ash disposal began in  the current permitted height of the phase i landfill is  feet msl the phase i coal ash landfill facility includes a sedimentation basin for collecting surface water runoff from the landfill area and haul road used for transporting ash from the power station to the landfill  plase ii landfill  permit application approved september   the phase ii landfill lies immediately west of and contiguous to the phase i landfill and will consist of two new cells cell   acres and cell   acres shown on drawing  the two cells are estimated to provide approximately  million cubic yards cy of disp